'''Bhapa''' or ('''Bhaapa'''<ref name="Mirror 2016">{{cite news |title=The Sardar joke is on you |work=Mumbai Mirror | date=3 January 2016 | url=http://www.mumbaimirror.com/columns/columnists/by-invitation/The-Sardar-joke-is-on-you/articleshow/50422145.cms | accessdate=17 May 2016}}</ref>) is a term used in [[Punjab region|Punjab]] by the members of the [[Sikh]] community in a pejorative sense <ref>{{cite news|title=Nihang Fateh Singh ousted Master Tara Singh from the Shiromani Akali Dal, ascribing Tara Singh’s professorial leanings as a sign of weakness implicit in the caste to which he belonged, rejecting him as a meek Bhapa – a pejorative slang for the merchant-class Khatri and Aroras – in an open forum.|url=http://www.newslaundry.com/2014/05/31/bluestar-baby-boomers/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The SAD’s chances will depend on the polarisation of Hindu votes and the extent to which urban Sikhs (Bhapas) would support a Hindu nominee.|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/punjab/patiala/cong-royals-fighting-to-hold-bastion-against-sad-s-juneja/article1-1251933.aspx|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150425074356/http://www.hindustantimes.com/punjab/patiala/cong-royals-fighting-to-hold-bastion-against-sad-s-juneja/article1-1251933.aspx|archivedate=2015-04-25|df=}}</ref> for Sikhs that migrated from Pakistan after the [[Partition of India]] in 1947.

''Bhapa'' describes Sikhs who migrated to India, especially from the [[Rawalpindi District|Rawalpindi area]], also known as the [[Khukhrain]]'s area, and its neighbouring regions. The Bhapa name at first was only associated with migrated Sikh traders/shopkeepers.<ref name="McLeod">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=xajcAwAAQBAJ |title=Historical Dictionary of Sikhism |first=W. H. |last=McLeod |authorlink=W. H. McLeod |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |year=2005}}</ref>{{pn|date=January 2018}}

''Bhapa'' was a common term for the elder brother or father, and is still often used in that sense. It is somewhat equivalent of ''[[sir]]''. Derived from [[Sanskrit]] ''Bappa'' or ''Vapra'',<ref>Monier Williams' Sanskrit-English Dictionary</ref> it is [[Cognate (etymology)|cognate]] to ''Bawa''.<ref>Gazetteer of the Bombay Presidency, Printed at the Govt. Central Press, 1896</ref> The term has occasionally been used as a royal title in some regions of India.  The best-known king with the title was [[Bappa Rawal]], the founder of the [[Guhilot]] dynasty.

