{{Spanish name 2|Larrobla|Pereyra}}
'''Juan Francisco de Larrobla Pereyra''' ([[Montevideo]], 9 January 1775 - [[Canelones, Uruguay|Canelones]], 5 July 1842) was a Uruguayan Roman Catholic cleric, theologian and patriot.
==Biography== Larrobla studied at the [[Real Colegio de San Carlos]] in [[Buenos Aires]] and afterwards [[theology]] at the [[National University of Córdoba|University of Córdoba]]. He was ordained priest shortly before 1800 and served in the [[Banda Oriental]]. Although a royalist, soon he had a feeling for the patriots.
On 25 August 1825 he presided over the House of Representatives of the [[Oriental Province]], an assembly of patriots which approved three Laws:<ref>[http://www.montevideo.com.uy/aclase/html/agosto.htm 25 August 1825]</ref> * Law of Independence (from the [[Empire of Brazil]]) * Law of Union (with the [[United Provinces of the River Plate]]) * Law of the [[Flag of Uruguay|National Flag]]
He was also involved in the improvement and expansion of the [[Cathedral of Canelones|Church of Our Lady of Guadalupe in Canelones]].<ref name="history">[http://www.diocesisdecanelones.com/index.php/es/nuesa-diocesis/historia.html History of the Cathedral of Canelones] {{es icon}}</ref>
==Family== His eldest sister Jacoba was mother of priest [[Lorenzo Antonio Fernández]].
His youngest brother [[Luis de la Robla]] was the first postmaster of independent Uruguay.
