{{Nihongo|'''Kawasaki Daishi'''|川崎大師|}} is the popular name of {{Nihongo|'''Heiken-ji'''|平間寺|Heiken-ji}}, a Buddhist temple in [[Kawasaki, Kanagawa|Kawasaki]], [[Japan]].  Founded in 1128, it is the headquarters of the [[Shingon-shū Chizan-ha|Chizan sect]] of [[Shingon Buddhism]].  Kawasaki Daishi is a popular temple for ''[[hatsumōde]]'' (the first visit to a place of worship in the new year).  In 2006, 2.72 million people engaged in ''hatsumōde'' here, the third largest figure in Japan and the largest in [[Kanagawa Prefecture]]. In 2016, the temple made preparations to receive 3 million visitors over the same period.<ref>{{Cite news |title=500,000 visitors descend on Ueno’s Ameyoko market |first=Roland |last=Shichijo |publisher=''[[Tokyo Reporter]]'' |date=December 31, 2016 |url=http://www.tokyoreporter.com/2016/12/31/500000-visitors-descend-on-uenos-ameyoko-market-for-new-years-shopping/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161231150245/http://www.tokyoreporter.com/2016/12/31/500000-visitors-descend-on-uenos-ameyoko-market-for-new-years-shopping/ |archive-date=December 31, 2016 |quote=Meanwhile in Kawasaki City, Kanagawa Prefecture, craftsmen at the Kawasaki Daishi Buddhist temple were making preparations to welcome some 3 million visitors over the sangainichi period, meaning the first three days of the New Year from Jan. 1 to Jan. 3, TV Asahi reports (Dec. 31).}}</ref> [[Keihin Electric Express Railway]], the oldest railroad company in the [[Kantō region]] of Japan, commenced service in January 1899 to carry passengers to Kawasaki Daishi from [[Tokyo]].

Heiken-ji is known formally as {{nihongo|'''Kongōzan Kinjōin Heiken-ji'''|金剛山金乗院平間寺|}}.<ref name="about"/>

